Introduction

--This project focuses on the design and implementation of a software system for sensor-based data acquisition(grabing real life Data), signal processing(cleaing the data), and visualization(displaying the final results).
 The primary objective // the main requrements is to develop a platform // system that is capable of loading time-series datasets, applying signal processing techniques, and presenting meaningful insights through graphical representations.

--The motivation behind this project is to simulate real-world signal analysis systems commonly used in biomedical and environmental applications.
 By working with datasets such as ECG, respiration, and temperature signals, the system demonstrates how raw sensor data can be transformed into useful information through preprocessing, filtering, and frequency analysis.

--To ensure the system meets its intended goals, both functional and non-functional requirements were considered. Functional requirements define the core capabilities 
of the system, such as loading CSV files, applying filters, computing statistical metrics, and displaying results. Non-functional requirements focus on system quality,
 including usability, responsiveness, and robustness when handling large datasets.

--Another important aspect of the project is the selection of appropriate datasets for testing and validation. Publicly available datasets were used to ensure realistic signal
 characteristics and reliable evaluation of the implemented methods.

--To verify correctness, the processed signals are compared with the original raw data through graphical visualization. Time-domain plots and frequency-domain analysis using FFT 
allow for clear observation of noise reduction and signal enhancement.

--Finally, the system is designed with user experience in mind by implementing a simple and intuitive graphical user interface (GUI). This allows users to easily load data, picking which type of data that the user wants to processe apply 
processing techniques(that is picking out Passing_Filter), and interpret results without requiring advanced technical knowledge(displaying it to the user).

For our project view we depended on this diagram:

--CSV Input → Preprocessing → Filtering → FFT Analysis → Feature Extraction → Visualization
(this diagrm/squential pipeline: was our guidline on how to build our system // the processe of the system  )

Signal Processing Methodology
3.1 Preprocessing

Raw sensor data may contain missing or corrupted values. These values are handled using interpolation techniques to ensure continuity in the signal. This step is essential for accurate filtering and analysis.


3.2 Digital Filtering

Digital filters are used to improve signal quality:

Low-Pass Filter (LPF): Removes high-frequency noise.
High-Pass Filter (HPF): Eliminates baseline drift.
Band-Pass Filter (BPF): Isolates the frequency range of interest.

For example:

ECG signals are filtered between 0.5–40 Hz to isolate cardiac activity.
Respiration signals are filtered between 0.1–0.5 Hz to capture breathing patterns.


3.3Frequency-Domain Analysis (FFT)

The Fast Fourier Transform (FFT) is used to convert signals from the time domain to the frequency domain. 
This allows identification of dominant frequency components, which are useful for detecting periodic patterns such as heart rate and breathing rate.

4. Implementation Details

The system is implemented using Python due to its powerful libraries for signal processing and visualization.

4.1 Tools and Libraries
NumPy (numerical operations)
Pandas (CSV handling)
SciPy (signal processing)
Matplotlib (visualization)
Tkinter (GUI development)


4.2 GUI Design

The graphical user interface includes:

File loading functionality
Signal type selection
Buttons for applying filters
FFT visualization
Display of statistical metrics

The GUI is designed to be simple and user-friendly, allowing users to interact with the system easily.

5. Testing & Evaluation
5.1 Datasets Used

The system was tested using:

Laboratory ECG dataset
Publicly available temperature dataset
Public respiration dataset

5.2 Results

The results demonstrate that:

Filtering effectively reduces noise
FFT correctly identifies dominant frequencies
Feature extraction provides meaningful insights
which we can see the figures at the demo presentation folder

5.3 Discussion

The system successfully processes different types of signals and adapts filtering techniques accordingly. 
The comparison between raw and processed signals shows significant improvement in signal clarity.



6.Conclusion

This project successfully demonstrates the development of a complete signal processing system capable of handling sensor-based datasets. 
The system integrates data loading, preprocessing, filtering, frequency analysis, and visualization into a single platform.
The results confirm that the implemented methods effectively improve signal quality and extract meaningful features. 
Future improvements could include real-time data processing and advanced feature extraction techniques.




